    "summary": "The Entente Cordiale, signed between Britain and France in April 1904, resolved long-standing colonial disputes between the two powers and established the foundation of the alliance that would fight [[event:110|World War I]] together. The agreement settled competing claims in Morocco and Egypt — France recognized British dominance in Egypt in exchange for British recognition of French primacy in Morocco — along with smaller disputes in West Africa, Newfoundland, and Southeast Asia.\n\nThe Entente was not a formal military alliance but a diplomatic understanding that dramatically improved relations between the two countries, which had been rivals and occasional enemies for centuries, most recently during the Fashoda Incident of 1898. Within a decade, it evolved into a de facto military alliance through a series of staff conversations, naval arrangements, and ultimately the commitment to fight together in 1914. The Entente also drew in Russia through the Triple Entente of 1907, creating the alliance bloc that would oppose the Central Powers in the coming world war.",
